<HEADLINE>
<P>
FROM THE VAULTS; SAM COOKE, RECORD MOGUL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Robert Hilburn 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *** 1/2; VARIOUS ARTISTS, "Sam Cooke's SAR Records Story" ( ABKCO ) 
</P>
<P>
 Beware: Though the front cover of this two-disc set is an adoring drawing of 
the late Sam Cooke, this isn't a greatest-hits package. Indeed, Cooke -- whose 
sweet, soulful singing style influenced everyone from Otis Redding to Rod 
Stewart -- is represented vocally only on a few rarities, including the demo of 
his 1957 hit "You Send Me." 
</P>
<P>
 Don't let that keep you away from the package, however, if you are a serious 
fan of the man behind such early-'60s gems as "Bring It on Home to Me" and "A 
Change Is Gonna Come." The set offers a fascinating look into the musical 
vision of one of the chief architects of modern soul music. 
</P>
<P>
 Not only was he co-owner of SAR Records, but he also wrote or produced several 
of the tracks, combining gospel, R&B and pop in exciting ways as he worked with 
such artists as the Soul Stirrers, Johnnie Taylor and the Valentinos (who did 
the original "It's All Over Now," later a hit for the Rolling Stones). 
</P>
<P>
 This isn't as essential as Cooke's own recordings, but the set adds greatly to 
our appreciation of his contribution to modern pop music. 
</P>
<P>
 New albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor) to four stars (excellent). 
A rating of five stars is reserved for deserving reissues and compilations.  
</P>
<P>
 Robert Hilburn 
</P>
</TEXT>
