<HEADLINE>
<P>
KUDOS TO THE DRIVERS OF MTA'S BUSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I am not arguing with Michelle Williams, who has given up riding the bus ("The 
End of the Line," Sept. 12). 
</P>
<P>
 But I came three years ago from Phoenix, where public transportation does not 
exist.I decided to leave my car behind, knowing your congested traffic and your 
daring drivers. 
</P>
<P>
 So I was dependent on the transportation system and for this I will be ever 
grateful. Certainly there are no more caring, helpful, kind people in this city 
or any city than the bus drivers of the MTA. They are patient and helpful, and 
they meet hundreds, perhaps thousands of different people daily. They are 
unsung and unappreciated heroes. 
</P>
<P>
 I cannot count the number of stories I have heard on bus rides. You would not 
believe the intimate tales that are told to fellow bus travelers and drivers. 
</P>
<P>
 Nor will you believe that while waiting for a bus, I met a most unusual woman 
who has turned out to be one of my best friends in this remarkable city. 
</P>
<P>
 JEANNETTE K. MULTER 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
