<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: VENTURA; VOLUNTEERS JOIN TO CLEAN UP VENTURA HIGH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 About 450 students, parents and community members converged Saturday on 
Ventura High School for the campus' fourth annual cleanup day. 
</P>
<P>
 The effort to spiff up the school was part of a program called Students 
Earning Revenue for Ventura High School Enrichment, or SERVE. 
</P>
<P>
 Starting at 8 a.m., about 350 students and 100 parents and other volunteers 
used brooms, sponges, mops and heavier equipment to attack the dirt and grime 
that have built up at the school over the last year. 
</P>
<P>
 A few spent hours digging trenches for a new sprinkling system. The crew of 
volunteers finished at about 2 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had a great day and got a ton of stuff done," said Assistant Principal 
Larry Emrich. "It was just super." 
</P>
<P>
 Many local businesses chipped in by donating goods and services, Emrich said. 
The students collected pledges for each hour of work they put in, raising about 
$7,500, Emrich said. 
</P>
<P>
 Most of the money will go back to various school organizations, based on the 
designations of the student volunteers, officials said. About 4% of the 
proceeds will go toward administrative costs. SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
