<HEADLINE>
<P>
DESTINATION: PENNSYLVANIA; JUST WONDER-FALL; FRANK LLOYD WRIGHT'S FALLINGWATER 
STILL LOOKS LIKE A HOME, NOT THE MUSEUM IT IS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BENJAMIN FORGEY, WASHINGTON POST 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fallingwater, the quintessential house in the woods, never ceases to astonish 
and delight. Nestled just so in the dappled light of the forest, extended 
breathtakingly over the fall of a backwoods creek, it is a wonder full of 
wonders, a weekend retreat that is as thrilling in its way as any great 
cathedral. 
</P>
<P>
 Conceived in 1935 by Frank Lloyd Wright, America's indubitable architectural 
genius, it was enjoyed for nearly three decades by the adventurous Pittsburgh 
family for whom it was built. Then, in 1963, it began its second career as a 
public trust -- becoming, in the words of one Wright scholar, "perhaps the 
best-known private home for someone not of royal blood in the history of the 
world." 
</P>
<P>
 Well might the keepers of Washington's Mount Vernon and Jefferson's Monticello 
dispute this tentative assertion, but it's true Fallingwater is unique. We 
honor this southwestern Pennsylvania home not because of who lived there or who 
visited but because Wright designed it at the very peak of his creativity. The 
house he created is comfortable and ingenious and, in ways small and large, 
elevating. 
</P>
<P>
 This by no means is to deny the importance of Edgar and Liliane Kaufmann, 
whose house it was. Design-conscious owners of Pittsburgh department stores, 
they deserve everlasting thanks for commissioning Wright as architect, for 
paying to get the house built -- it cost more than $120,000, nearly four times 
the initial estimate -- and simply for getting through with humor intact the 
oft-tiresome trial of dealing with the great artist. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Their son and only child, Edgar Kaufmann Jr., likewise deserves enormous 
credit. As a young man he apprenticed briefly at Wright's famous studio, 
Taliesin, in Spring Green, Wis., and therefore was able to introduce his 
parents to the architect. 
</P>
<P>
 He donated the house and surrounding land to a trust in 1963, together with an 
endowment for upkeep. And he oversaw the property with a sympathetic eye until 
his death in 1989, insisting always that it be kept as accessible as possible. 
</P>
<P>
 Signs of the Kaufmanns' occupancy abound in the house turned museum. Artworks 
the couple bought for the house -- including African wood carvings, Chinese 
lacquers, American ceramics, a drawing by Diego Rivera, a bronze by Jacques 
Lipchitz -- remain in their preferred places. A large oil portrait of a robust 
Edgar Sr. still commands a view of the dining area. The rustic Italian chairs 
that Liliane Kaufmann liked -- and Wright didn't -- still surround the dining 
table. Guides on the 45-minute tours don't fail to point out that the three 
wooden legs make the chairs more stable on the rough stone floor than 
four-legged chairs would be. 
</P>
<P>
 Indeed, despite the fact that hundreds of visitors trudge through each day, 
the house retains a lived-in charm, as if awaiting the momentary return of its 
original owners. 
</P>
<P>
 Though today's guests are forbidden to sit on them, the cushions of Wright's 
built-in sofas are covered with the same kind of richly woven beige material as 
always, and the stone floors of the spacious living-dining room are decorated 
with the same kind of warm-toned Berber rugs. This naturalness was what Edgar 
Jr. wanted, explains chief curator Lynda Waggoner: "It's supposed to look like 
a house, not a state museum." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 If one were to make a list of things to remember about Fallingwater, it might 
start with the floors, if only to prove the point that every aspect of the 
design is interconnected. 
</P>
<P>
 Made of irregularly shaped slabs of "Pottsville" sandstone -- the stone used 
throughout the house, and quarried on the property -- the floors are appealing 
to the eye and touch. 
</P>
<P>
 Wright had the stones waxed to look as if they were under a shallow, rippling 
current of clear water, an apt reference to currents of the stream running 
under the house and a subtle metaphor for the philosophy behind the entire 
design. 
</P>
<P>
 Fallingwater is perhaps the most compelling manifestation of Wright's belief 
that architecture is not opposed to nature but, rather, is another facet or 
expression of nature and its processes. 
</P>
<P>
 Obviously, he sensed the potential of the site when the Kaufmanns first took 
him to their picturesque corner of the woods: They liked to stand on a rock 
ledge and look at the waterfall and they thought, conventionally, that a house 
should do the same. Wright, by contrast, seized the opportunity to make the 
house part of the waterfall. 
</P>
<P>
 The forces that hold Fallingwater up, that make possible its stupendous 
cantilevered balconies, are but natural forces properly understood and 
correctly built with reinforced concrete.  
</P>
<P>
 The persistent doubts that Wright's imagination outstripped his command of 
structural engineering have recently been put to rest, Waggoner reports, by 
exhaustive engineering studies that confirm the house is structurally sound. 
</P>
<P>
 That does not mean there aren't problems. For one thing, Fallingwater leaks. 
Water -- melting snow and rain -- reportedly gets in through the roof, the 
walls, sometimes even the floor under which the stream known as Bear Run flows. 
</P>
<P>
 This keeps workers busy year-round shoveling snow off the roof, mopping, 
patching leaks and making more substantive repairs. But given the fact that 
Fallingwater is a 60-year-old house with a flat roof, built to nestle in close 
communion with nature, many achitects seem to feel that it has actually held up 
quite well.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 For Wright, cantilevering was a philosophy as well as a structural system. He 
used it here wherever he could. Fallingwater's bookshelves and display shelves 
and even the metal arm holding the great round pot above the fire are 
cantilevered too. 
</P>
<P>
 Probably no great house has ever had such an inconspicuous entryway as that at 
Fallingwater. The doorway is hidden away, as if by accident of nature, and it 
is dark and narrow, as if the house were a cave. Wright was known for his 
sheltered entryways, and this is the most sheltered of them all. It is the 
beginning of a spatial flow of surprise and discovery that is the most wondrous 
of Fallingwater's wonders. One moves constantly from closed to open, inside to 
outside, dark to light and back again. It's refreshing and spirit-lifting. 
</P>
<P>
 Along the way there are opportunities to pause in such marvels as the corner 
niche that Edgar Jr. used as his study. 
</P>
<P>
 Located on the third floor of the vertical part of the house -- a strong 
counterbalance to a composition of sweeping horizontals -- the little room is 
in itself a study of shadows and lights. 
</P>
<P>
 There's a built-in desk with a quarter-circle cut in its top to accommodate an 
inward-opening casement window. Right next to that, there's a corner made 
top-to-bottom of casement windows that open outward so that, when they're 
opened, the corner seems to disappear before your eyes. 
</P>
<P>
 The tours are pleasantly paced, the guides friendly and knowledgeable. The 
thing they do best is make you want to come back soon. GUIDEBOOK 
</P>
<P>
 Falling for Fallingwater 
</P>
<P>
 Getting there: Fallingwater is about two hours' driving time from Pittsburgh 
via Interstate 70/76 (Pennsylvania Turnpike), then south on Pennsylvania Route 
381. The house is halfway between the villages of Mill Run and Ohiopyle.  
</P>
<P>
 Dates, hours, rules: Fallingwater is open six days a week to mid-November, 10 
a.m.-4 p.m. Closed Mondays. Weekend tours are available from mid-November 
through March, weather permitting (weekday winter tours only by special 
arrangement). Weekday admission is $6 per person, weekends $10. Two-hour 
"in-depth" tours are offered at 8:30 a.m., by advance reservation only, at $25 
per person. Still photography inside the house is permitted only on these 
tours. 
</P>
<P>
 "Since considerable walking and numerous steps are involved," says the 
Fallingwater brochure, "some elderly people and those with medical problems may 
find the tour too strenuous." The first floor of the house is 
wheelchair-accessible, and there is a video showing the upper floors. Children 
under 9 years old are not permitted on the house tours. There is a child-care 
center on the property, available at $2 per child per hour. 
</P>
<P>
 Reservations: Do not go without them. Wright's popularity continues to climb, 
and with it, attendance at Fallingwater. Tours are running near capacity 
year-round, and October is a BIG month. 
</P>
<P>
 Where to stay: The Nemacolin Woodlands Resort (412-329-8555) in Farmington is, 
as the name implies, a complete package. An 800-acre estate, it offers golf (18 
holes), tennis, swimming, croquet and hiking, in addition to rooms in the inn 
and condominium units. Rates range $195-$395 per night. 
</P>
<P>
 The Mount Summit Inn (412-438-8594), on a mountaintop near Farmington, is a 
resort destination offering a similar range of activities, including a 
nine-hole golf course. Dating to 1907, the inn has rates of $69-$131 per night. 
</P>
<P>
 Failinger's Gunter Hotel (301-689-6511), in Frostburg, Md., is a find and a 
bargain. A mid-town hotel dating to 1897, it has been restored to (almost) 
former glory by Kermit and Thelma Failinger, known to all of Frostburg as Jake 
and Beanie. The lobby's sweeping oak staircase is a step back in time. Rates 
are $45-$55 per night. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information: Fallingwater, P.O. Box R, Mill Run, Pa. 15464; tel. 
(412) 329-8501. Bureau of Travel Marketing, Room 453 Forum Building, Dept. PR 
901, Harrisburg 17120; (717) 787-5453. 
</P>
</TEXT>
